Package sprouts

Interface Association<K,V>

Type Parameters:
K - The type of the keys in this association, which must be immutable.
V - The type of the values in this association, which should be immutable.
All Superinterfaces:
Iterable<Pair<K,V>>
public interface Association<K,V> extends Iterable<Pair<K,V>>
Defines an association between keys and values as an immutable value object where the values are accessed by the keys in a map-like fashion. An association cannot contain duplicate keys, and each key can map to at most one value.

You may think of this as a Map but without the ability to modify the association after it has been created. Instead, you may create a new association with the desired changes using methods like put(Object, Object) or remove(Object), which will return a new association with the changes applied.

Note: Mutable objects should not be stored in an association, especially keys, whose hash codes and equality has to stay constant for the lifetime of the association, which assumes that their behavior does not change (key code hash caching for example). The behavior of this class is uncertain if a key is changed in a manner that affects equals or hashCode after it has been added to the association.

    • collectorOf

      static <K, V> Collector<Pair<? extends K,? extends V>,?,Association<K,V>> collectorOf(Class<K> keyType, Class<V> valueType)
      A collector that can be used to collect key-value pairs from a Java Stream of Pair instances into an association. The types of the keys and values in the association have to be defined when using this collector.
      Here is an example demonstrating how this method may be used:
      
    var assoc = Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
                .map( it -> Pair.of(it.hashCode(), it.toUpperCase()) )
                .collect(Association.collectorOf(Integer.class, String.class));
      This will create a new association between integers and strings where the integers are the hash codes of the strings and the values are the upper case versions of the strings.
      If there are null values in the stream, an exception will be thrown, because an association cannot contain null keys or values.
      Type Parameters:
      K - The type of the keys in the association, which must be immutable and have value object semantics.
      V - The type of the values in the association, which should be immutable.
      Parameters:
      keyType - The type of the keys in the association to collect.
      valueType - The type of the values in the resulting association.
      Returns:
      A collector that can be used to collect key-value pairs into an association.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - If any of the supplied type parameters is null.

      This will create a new-ordered association between integers and strings where the integers are the hash codes of the strings and the values are the upper case versions of the strings.
      If there are null values in the stream, an exception will be thrown, because an association cannot contain null keys or values.

    • collectorOfSorted

      static <K, V> Collector<Pair<? extends K,? extends V>,?,Association<K,V>> collectorOfSorted(Class<K> keyType, Class<V> valueType, Comparator<K> comparator)
      A collector that can be used to collect key-value pairs from a Java Stream of Pair instances into an association with the given key and value types, where the keys are sorted using the provided comparator. The types of the keys and values in the association have to be defined when using this collector.
      Here is an example demonstrating how this method may be used:
      
    var assoc = Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
                .map( it -> Pair.of(it.hashCode(), it.toUpperCase()) )
                .collect(Association.collectorOfSorted(Integer.class, String.class, Comparator.naturalOrder()));
      This will create a new-ordered association between integers and strings where the integers are the hash codes of the strings and the values are the upper case versions of the strings.
      If there are null values in the stream, an exception will be thrown because an association cannot contain null keys or values.
      Type Parameters:
      K - The type of the keys in the association, which must be immutable and have value object semantics.
      V - The type of the values in the association, which should be immutable.
      Parameters:

      valueType - The type of the values in the resulting association.
      comparator - The comparator to use for sorting the keys in the association.
      Returns:
      A collector that can be used to collect key-value pairs into an ordered association.

    • putIfAbsent

      Association<K,V> putIfAbsent(K key, V value)
      If the specified key is not already associated with a value associates it with the given value and returns null, else returns the current value.

      This is equivalent to the following code, but is implemented as a single operation that is atomic: 

       
 V existing = association.get(key).orElse(null);
 if (existing == null)
     association = association.put(key, aValue);
      Parameters:
      key - key with which the specified value is to be associated
      value - value to be associated with the specified key
      Returns:
      The updated value associated with the specified key, or this (unchanged) association if the key was already associated with a value.

    • update

      default Association<K,V> update(K key, Function<V,V> updater)
      Returns a new association where the value associated with the given key is transformed using the provided update function, but only if the key exists in this association. If the key is not present, this association is returned unchanged.

      This method provides a safe and convenient way to modify existing values without having to manually check for key existence or handle Optional values.

      Example usage: 
      
    var ages = Association.of("Haruka", 24)
                            .put("Josh", 28)
                            .put("Tom", 20);

    var updatedAges = ages.update("Haruka", age -> age + 5)
                          .update("Tom", age -> age * 2);

    // The result: Haruka=29, Josh=28, Tom=40
      Parameters:
      key - The key whose associated value should be updated. It must not be null.
      updater - A function that takes the current value and returns a new value. The function will only be called if the key exists. Must not be null.
      Returns:
      A new association with the updated value if the key existed, or this association unchanged if the key was not found.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either the key or updater function is null.
      NullPointerException - if the updater function returns null (associations cannot contain null values).
      See Also:
      • For adding or replacing values regardless of existence
      • For replacing existing values only
      • For adding values only when the key is absent

    • updateAll

      default Association<K,V> updateAll(Tuple<K> keys, Function<V,V> updater)
      Returns a new association where the values associated with all the given keys are transformed using the provided update function, but only for keys that exist in this association. Keys that are not present in the association are silently ignored.

      This method provides a convenient way to batch-update multiple values in a single operation, making it ideal for scenarios where you need to apply the same transformation to multiple existing entries.

      Example usage: 
      
   var inventory = Association.of("apples", 10)
                              .put("oranges", 15)
                              .put("bananas", 20)
                              .put("grapes", 8);

   // A user bought 2 oranges and grapes each.
   var inventory = inventory.updateAll(
                     Tuple.of("oranges", "grapes"),
                     quantity -> quantity - 2
                   );

   // The result: apples=10, oranges=13, bananas=20, grapes=6
      Parameters:
      keys - A tuple of keys whose associated values should be updated.
      updater - A function that takes the current value and returns a new value. The function will only be called for keys that exist. Must not be null.
      Returns:
      A new association with the updated values for all existing keys in the provided tuple, or this association unchanged if none of the keys were found.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either the keys tuple or updater function is null.
      NullPointerException - if the updater function returns null for any value.
      See Also:
      • For updating a single value
      • For updating values using a ValueSet of keys
      • For updating values using any collection of keys

    • updateAll

      default Association<K,V> updateAll(Collection<? extends K> keys, Function<V,V> updater)
      Returns a new association where the values associated with all the keys in the supplied collection are transformed using the update function, but only for keys that exist in this association. Keys that are not present in the association are silently ignored.

      This method offers the most flexibility as it accepts any Collection implementation, making it easy to integrate with existing Java collections.

      Example usage: 
      
   var productPrices = Association.of("laptop", 999.99)
                                  .put("mouse", 25.50)
                                  .put("keyboard", 75.00)
                                  .put("monitor", 299.99);

   // List of products going on sale
   var saleProducts = List.of("mouse", "keyboard", "headphones");

   // Apply 15% discount to sale products
   var salePrices = productPrices.updateAll(
       saleProducts,
       price -> price * 0.85  // 15% discount
   );

   // The result: laptop=999.99, mouse=21.675, keyboard=63.75, monitor=299.99
   // Note: "headphones" was ignored since it wasn't in the original association
      Parameters:
      keys - A collection of keys whose associated values should be updated.
      updater - A function that takes the current value and returns a new value. The function will only be called for keys that exist. Must not be null.
      Returns:
      A new association with the updated values for all existing keys in the provided collection, or this association unchanged if none of the keys were found.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either the keys collection or updater function is null.
      NullPointerException - if the updater function returns null for any value.
      See Also:
      • For updating a single value
      • For updating values using a Tuple of keys
      • For updating values using a ValueSet of keys

    • updateAll

      default Association<K,V> updateAll(Stream<? extends K> keys, Function<V,V> updater)
      Returns a new association where the values associated with the keys from the supplied stream are transformed using the update function, but only for keys that exist in this association. Keys that are not present in the association are silently ignored.

      This method is ideal for scenarios where you have a stream of keys, such as when filtering or processing keys from another data source, and want to efficiently apply updates to the corresponding values.

      Example usage: 
      
   var websiteStats = Association.of("/home", 1500)
                                 .put("/about", 800)
                                 .put("/contact", 300)
                                 .put("/products", 1200)
                                 .put("/blog", 950);

   // Update page views for high-traffic pages (over 1000 views)
   var updatedStats = websiteStats.updateAll(
       websiteStats.entrySet().stream()
                   .filter(entry -> entry.second() > 1000)
                   .map(Pair::first),  // Stream of high-traffic page keys
       views -> views + 100  // Add 100 bonus views for high performers
   );

   // The result: /home=1600, /about=800, /contact=300, /products=1300, /blog=950
      Parameters:
      keys - A stream of keys whose associated values should be updated.
      updater - A function that takes the current value and returns a new value. The function will only be called for keys that exist. Must not be null.
      Returns:
      A new association with the updated values for all existing keys in the provided stream, or this association unchanged if none of the keys were found.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if either the keys stream or updater function is null.
      NullPointerException - if the updater function returns null for any value.
      See Also:
      • For updating a single value
      • For updating values using a Tuple of keys
      • For updating values using a ValueSet of keys
      • For updating values using any collection of keys

    • removeIf

      default Association<K,V> removeIf(Predicate<Pair<K,V>> filter)
      Creates an updates Association where all key/value pairs satisfying the given Predicate, are removed. Or in other words, if Predicate.test(Object) yields true for a particular entry Pair, then it will be removed, otherwise, it will remain in the returned association.
      Note that errors or runtime exceptions thrown during iteration or by the predicate are relayed to the caller.
      Parameters:
      filter - A function which takes in a key/value Pair, and returns true to trigger its removal and false to ensure it is kept.
      Returns:
      An updated Association where elements are removed according to the supplied predicate test, or this instance if nothing was removed.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - - if the specified filter is null

    • equals

      boolean equals(Object o)
      Compares the specified object with this association for value equality. Returns true only if the specified object is also an association with the same size(), keyType(), valueType(), and where every key value pair in the specified association is contained in this association (or equivalently, every member of this association is contained in the specified association). Additionally, two associations must also report the same values for isLinked() and isSorted(). This definition ensures that the equals method works properly across different implementations of the association interface.
      Overrides:
      equals in class Object
      Parameters:
      o - object to be compared for equality with this association
      Returns:
      true if the specified object is equal to this association in terms of value semantic.

    • hashCode

      int hashCode()
      Returns the hash code value for this association. The hash code of an association is defined to be the sum of the hash codes of the pairs in the association. This ensures that a1.equals(a2) implies that a1.hashCode()==a2.hashCode() for any two associations a1 and a2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode().
      Overrides:
      hashCode in class Object
      Returns:
      The hash code value for this association as a 32-bit integer, based on the sum of the hash codes of all pairs in this association.
